   • What These Configurations Do

     All three examples configure the same essential pieces:

       1. *‘org-todo-keywords’* - Defines the workflow states (TODO →
          NEXT → WAIT → DONE/CNCL)
             • The ‘|’ separator marks done states (right side) vs
               active states (left side)
             • All GTD keywords must be in a single sequence

       2. *‘org-gtd-keyword-mapping’* - Maps GTD concepts to your
          keyword choices
             • ‘todo’ - Tasks not yet actionable
             • ‘next’ - Tasks ready to work on right now
             • ‘wait’ - Tasks blocked or delegated
             • ‘done’ - Tasks successfully completed
             • ‘canceled’ - Tasks that won't be done

       3. *‘org-gtd-directory’* - Where org-gtd keeps its files
          (defaults to ‘~/gtd/’)

       4. *‘org-agenda-files’* - Makes org-gtd items appear in agenda
          views

       5. *‘org-edna-mode’* - REQUIRED for projects to work

       6. *Keybindings* - Three types:
             • *Global bindings*: Work anywhere in Emacs (capture,
               engage, process, etc.)
             • *Clarify map binding*: Only works when organizing items
               in clarify buffers
             • *Agenda map binding*: Quick task actions in agenda views
               (‘C-c .’ for ‘org-gtd-agenda-transient’)

   • Testing Your Configuration

     After adding one of the configurations above and restarting Emacs,
     verify everything works:

     *Test 1: Capture works*

          M-x org-gtd-capture

     Expected: Opens a capture buffer for the inbox.

     If it fails: Check that ‘org-gtd-directory’ exists and you have
     write permissions.

     *Test 2: Engage works*

          M-x org-gtd-engage

     Expected: Opens an agenda view (might be empty if you haven't
     organized anything yet).

     If it fails: Check that ‘org-agenda-files’ includes your GTD
     directory.

     *Test 3: Keywords are recognized*

       1. Open any org file: ‘M-x find-file ~/test.org’
       2. Type: ‘* Test heading’
       3. Put cursor on the heading
       4. Try cycling TODO states: ‘C-c C-t’

     Expected: Should cycle through TODO → NEXT → WAIT → DONE → CNCL.

     If it fails: Check that ‘org-todo-keywords’ is set correctly.

     *Test 4: org-edna is enabled*

          M-x describe-variable RET org-edna-mode

     Expected: Should show "t" (enabled).

     If it fails: Make sure ‘(org-edna-mode 1)’ is in your config and
     you've restarted Emacs.

   • Common Configuration Problems

     Before troubleshooting, identify which configuration style you're
     using:
        • *Vanilla Emacs*: See *note Example 1 Vanilla Emacs: Example 1
          Vanilla Emacs (Minimal Configuration).
        • *Doom Emacs*: See *note Example 2 Doom Emacs: Example 2 Doom
          Emacs Configuration.
        • *Spacemacs*: See *note Example 3 Spacemacs: Example 3
          Spacemacs Configuration.

     Each example shows the complete, correct configuration for that
     environment.

     *Problem: "org-gtd-capture" is undefined*

     *Cause*: org-gtd package isn't installed or loaded.

     *Solution*:
        • *Vanilla Emacs*: Install from MELPA with ‘M-x package-install
          RET org-gtd RET’
        • *Doom Emacs*: Add ‘(package! org-gtd)’ to your ‘packages.el’
          and run ‘doom sync’
        • *Spacemacs*: The ‘use-package’ form in the *note Spacemacs
          example: Example 3 Spacemacs Configuration. automatically
          installs it with ‘:ensure t’

     *Problem: Keywords don't change when I press C-c C-t*

     *Cause*: ‘org-todo-keywords’ not configured correctly.

     *Solution*: Check your configuration has this setting:
          (setq org-todo-keywords
                '((sequence "TODO" "NEXT" "WAIT" "|" "DONE" "CNCL")))

     Common mistakes:
        • Keywords not in quotes: Should be ‘"TODO"’ not ‘TODO’
        • Missing sequence wrapper: Need ‘'((sequence ...))’ not just
          ‘'("TODO" ...)’
        • No done separator: Need ‘|’ before ‘"DONE"’ and ‘"CNCL"’

     See the complete configuration for your environment above.

     *Problem: Projects don't advance when I mark tasks DONE*

     *Cause*: org-edna isn't enabled.

     *Solution*: All three configuration examples include
     ‘(org-edna-mode 1)’.  Make sure you have:
        • *Vanilla/Spacemacs*: ‘(org-edna-mode 1)’ in the ‘:config’
          section
        • *Doom*: ‘(org-edna-mode)’ in the ‘:config’ section (Doom
          handles the argument)

     *Problem: Can't see GTD items in agenda*

     *Cause*: GTD directory not in ‘org-agenda-files’.

     *Solution*: All three configuration examples include this.  Check
     you have:
          ;; For plain elisp - must be AFTER org-gtd loads
          (with-eval-after-load 'org-gtd
            (setq org-agenda-files (list org-gtd-directory)))

     Or if using ‘use-package’ / ‘use-package!’, put it in ‘:config’
     (not ‘:custom’):
          :config
          (setq org-agenda-files (list org-gtd-directory))

     *Problem: Keybindings don't work*

     *Cause*: Keybindings not defined, or defined incorrectly for your
     environment.

     *Solution*:
        • *Vanilla Emacs*: Use ‘global-set-key’ for global commands,
          ‘define-key org-gtd-clarify-mode-map’ for clarify buffer
          commands
        • *Doom Emacs*: Use ‘map!’ with ‘:leader’ prefix for global,
          ‘:map org-gtd-clarify-mode-map’ for clarify buffer
        • *Spacemacs*: Use ‘spacemacs/set-leader-keys’ for global,
          ‘define-key’ for clarify buffer

     The clarify binding (‘C-c c’) *only works in clarify buffers* - you
     must run ‘M-x org-gtd-process-inbox’ first.

     See the complete configuration for your environment to copy the
     correct keybinding syntax.

   • Working with Your Existing Org Setup

     Already have org-mode configured with your own refile targets and
     archive location?  Org-gtd is designed to work *alongside* your
     existing setup, not replace it.

     *Quick answers:*

        • *Will org-gtd break my ‘org-refile-targets’?*  No.  Org-gtd
          merges its targets with yours.  Your targets appear first in
          completion.

        • *Will org-gtd ignore my ‘org-archive-location’?*  By default,
          yes—org-gtd uses year-based archive files.  But you can make
          it respect yours with one line:
               (setq org-gtd-archive-location nil)  ; Use your org-archive-location

     *How the merge works:*

     When you organize an item (say, as a Project), org-gtd builds a
     combined refile target list:

       1. Your ‘org-refile-targets’ (appears first)
       2. Any heading with ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE: Projects’ property
          (org-gtd's system)

     So if you have ‘org-refile-targets’ pointing to
     ‘~/org/projects.org’, that file's headings appear first.  Org-gtd's
     property-marked targets appear after.

     *When to use which:*

     Scenario                       What to do
     -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
     New to org-mode                Use org-gtd defaults.  It creates targets automatically.
     Have existing refile setup     Keep it!  Org-gtd adds to it, doesn't replace it.
     Want single archive file       Set ‘org-gtd-archive-location’ to ‘nil’, configure ‘org-archive-location’
     Want year-based GTD archives   Use org-gtd default (nothing to configure)

     *See also:* *note Refiling to the appropriate area:: for details on
     ‘ORG_GTD_REFILE’ properties, *note Cleaning up / archiving:
     Cleaning up / archiving completed work. for archive details.


