5.2.3 Clarifying each item
--------------------------

Clarifying an item means editing and adding the information that will be
most valuable to you to the item.  Note that task-specific information,
such as appointment date, or name of person to whom it is delegated, or
even area of focus, will be added during the Organize step, so don't
worry about these yet.

   • How to start clarifying

     Besides ending up in here automatically while processing the inbox,
     there's two more ways to enter the clarifying flow:

     ‘org-gtd-clarify-item’
          call this from any org-mode heading to do a one-off
          clarification.
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-agenda-item’
          call this from the agenda view, if you have anything you want
          to re-clarify, or possibly clarify for the first time, from
          somewhere outside the inbox.

   • data shape requirements

     There's two general shapes you'll be looking for.  Almost
     everything will look like a simple org-mode heading.  For instance,
     ‘* Task desc’.

     The only exception will be a project, that will look like a
     top-level heading for the project description with, underneath, a
     series of second-level headings representing each task to be
     executed sequentially before the project is complete.

          * Project heading
          ** First task
          ** Second task
          ** Third task

   • Options and commands related to clarification

     The clarify buffers use the major mode ‘org-gtd-clarify-mode’,
     which is derived from ‘org-mode’.  There is a keymap,
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-mode-map’, that you can use to bind useful
     keybindings.

     org-gtd provides three optional helper windows during
     clarification, each controlled by a variable:

     **Horizons window** — shows your GTD horizons file for context:
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-show-horizons’
          set to ‘'right’, ‘'left’, ‘'top’, or ‘'bottom’ to show by
          default; ‘nil’ to hide
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-toggle-horizons-window’
          command to toggle visibility

     See *note Working with the GTD Horizons:: for more details.

     **Organize help window** — shows all GTD item types with keyboard
     shortcuts:
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-show-organize-help’
          set to ‘'right’, ‘'left’, ‘'top’, or ‘'bottom’ to show by
          default; ‘nil’ to hide
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-toggle-organize-help’
          command to toggle visibility

     **Dependencies helper window** — shows task relationships when
     clarifying projects:
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-display-helper-buffer’
          set to ‘t’ to show when clarifying projects with multiple
          tasks; ‘nil’ to hide

     Try it now: while clarifying an item, run ‘M-x
     org-gtd-clarify-toggle-organize-help’.  You'll see each type's
     purpose and what happens when you choose it.

     If you are clarifying a project, you may be interested in project
     templates:
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-project-insert-template’
          a function that will ask you to choose a template to insert.
     ‘org-gtd-clarify-project-templates’
          an alist of the form ‘(name . template)’ where both name and
          template are strings.  ‘name’ will be used in the interactive
          menu, and ‘template’ will be inserted in the buffer.

     *See also*: *note Configuration Variables Reference:: for complete
     documentation of clarification options, and *note Commands
     Reference:: for all clarification commands.

   • Duplicating items during clarification

     Sometimes one inbox item represents multiple outcomes.  "Prepare
     for Monday meeting" might actually be three things: book the room,
     prepare the slides, and email the agenda.  The duplicate feature
     lets you split these apart during clarification.

     **Who needs this:** Anyone who captures quick notes that later turn
     out to be multiple separate actions or projects.

        • Your first duplicate in 30 seconds

            1. While clarifying any item, press ‘C-c d’
            2. Edit the title in the minibuffer (or keep it the same)
            3. Press ‘RET’

          That's it.  A queue window appears showing your duplicate.
          Continue clarifying and organizing the original item—the
          duplicate waits its turn.

        • Understanding the workflow

          Think of duplicates as a "spawn" operation.  You're clarifying
          item A, and you realize it's actually A, B, and C.  You spawn
          B and C as duplicates, then:

            1. Organize A (the original)
            2. Automatically, B opens for clarification
            3. Organize B
            4. Automatically, C opens for clarification
            5. Organize C
            6. Done—back to where you started

          The key insight: *duplicates form a mini-session*.  You must
          process all of them before returning to your previous context.
          This matches the GTD principle of fully processing what's in
          front of you before moving on.

        • The queue window

          When you create your first duplicate, a side window appears:

               Pending (2):
                 1. Book the room
                 2. Email the agenda

          This window:
             • Shows all queued duplicates by title
             • Updates as you add more or process them
             • Closes automatically when the last duplicate is organized
             • Position is configurable (default: bottom)

        • Two ways to duplicate

          Key       Command                             Behavior
          -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
          ‘C-c d’   ‘org-gtd-clarify-duplicate’         Prompts for new title (current title as default)
          ‘C-c D’   ‘org-gtd-clarify-duplicate-exact’   Copies exactly, no prompt

          Use ‘C-c d’ when the duplicates have different titles (most
          common).  Use ‘C-c D’ when you want identical copies to
          organize differently (e.g., same task delegated to multiple
          people).

        • What happens if you cancel?

          If you press ‘C-c C-k’ to stop clarifying while duplicates are
          queued, you'll see:

               2 pending duplicates:
                 - Book the room
                 - Email the agenda
               [d]iscard all  [s]ave to inbox  [c]ancel:

             • *Discard*: Duplicates are lost (you decided you don't
               need them)
             • *Save to inbox*: Duplicates are appended to your inbox
               for later processing
             • *Cancel*: Return to the clarify buffer (abort the abort)

        • Nested duplicates

          While clarifying a duplicate, you can create more duplicates.
          They append to the queue.  All must be processed before
          returning to your original context.

        • Data safety

          Duplicates exist only in memory until organized.  If Emacs
          crashes, they're lost.  However:

             • Before exiting Emacs normally, you'll be prompted if any
               clarify buffers have pending duplicates
             • You can save them to inbox or discard them
             • The WIP buffer itself has auto-save enabled, so your
               clarification work is protected

        • Configuration

               ;; Change queue window position (default: 'bottom)
               ;; Options: 'top, 'right, 'left, 'bottom
               (setq org-gtd-clarify-duplicate-queue-position 'right)

          *See also*: *note Commands Reference:: for
          ‘org-gtd-clarify-duplicate’ and
          ‘org-gtd-clarify-duplicate-exact’.


