5.2.5 Engaging with your GTD items
----------------------------------

You can see a list of all NEXT actions, and scheduled actions, with ‘M-x
org-gtd-engage’ .

   You can call ‘org-gtd-show-all-next’ to only see NEXT actions,
nothing scheduled.

   You can use ‘M-x org-gtd-reflect-missed-engagements’ to find
appointments you missed, delegated items needing check-ins, and late
projects.  This is your safety net for catching things that slipped
through the cracks.

   The weekly review is not yet implemented.

   • Quick Task Actions from the Agenda

        • First Contact: Why This Feature?

          When you're working from ‘org-gtd-engage’, you see your NEXT
          actions and scheduled items.  You want to mark things done,
          defer something to tomorrow, or clock in on a task - but you
          don't want to navigate away from your list.

          ‘org-gtd-agenda-transient’ gives you quick access to common
          task operations right from the agenda view.  One keypress,
          pick an action, and you're back to your list.

          *For GTD users* who spend time in their daily agenda and want
          to execute tasks efficiently without context-switching.

        • Black Triangle: Your First Quick Action

            1. Open your engage view: ‘C-c d e’ (or ‘M-x
               org-gtd-engage’)
            2. Move point to any task
            3. Press ‘C-c .’ (you'll need to set up the keybinding first
               - see below)
            4. Press ‘d’ to mark the task DONE

          That's it.  The task is done, and you're still in your agenda.

          *Setup:* Add this keybinding to your config:

               (define-key org-agenda-mode-map (kbd "C-c .") #'org-gtd-agenda-transient)

          For ‘use-package’, add this to your ‘:bind’ section:

               :bind
               (:map org-agenda-mode-map
                ("C-c ." . org-gtd-agenda-transient))

        • Understanding the Actions

          The transient menu is organized into groups based on what
          you're trying to do:

             • State Changes

               Change the TODO state of a task.  These are the most
               common actions:

                  • *Mark DONE* (‘d’) - You finished it
                  • *Set WAITING* (‘w’) - You're blocked on
                    something/someone
                  • *Set NEXT* (‘n’) - It's ready to work on
                  • *Cancel* (‘x’) - It's no longer relevant
                  • *Cycle TODO* (‘t’) - Cycle through all states

             • Time Adjustments (Conditional)

               For Calendar, Delegated, and Tickler items only - these
               have GTD timestamps that determine when they appear.

                  • *Defer 1 day* (‘+’) - Push it to tomorrow (quick
                    snooze)
                  • *Set date* (‘s’) - Pick a new date (calls
                    ‘org-gtd-set-timestamp’)

               Why only these types?  Calendar items have appointment
               dates.  Delegated items have follow-up dates.  Tickler
               items have "remind me on" dates.  Habits are excluded
               because deferring a habit has different semantics (you'd
               break the streak).

               *Note*: You can also call ‘org-gtd-set-timestamp’
               directly from an org-mode heading (not just from the
               agenda).  This is useful when editing a Calendar,
               Delegated, or Tickler item in its source file.

             • Clocking

               Track time spent on tasks:

                  • *Clock in* (‘I’) - Start the clock
                  • *Clock out* (‘O’) - Stop the clock

             • Metadata

               Add context to tasks:

                  • *Set effort* (‘e’) - Estimate how long it'll take
                  • *Set priority* (‘,’) - A/B/C priority
                  • *Set tags* (‘:’) - Add tags for filtering
                  • *Add note* (‘z’) - Append a note (logged with
                    timestamp)
                  • *Area of focus* (‘a’) - Set which life area this
                    belongs to

             • Clarify

               Sometimes you need to rethink a task:

                  • *Clarify (refile)* (‘c’) - Open the clarify
                    workflow, refile when done
                  • *Clarify (in place)* (‘C’) - Open the clarify
                    workflow, keep in same GTD location

        • Command Reference

          Key   Action               Description
          ----------------------------------------------------------------------
          ‘d’   Mark DONE            Complete the task
          ‘w’   Set WAITING          Mark as blocked/waiting
          ‘n’   Set NEXT             Mark as ready to work on
          ‘x’   Cancel               Cancel the task
          ‘t’   Cycle TODO           Cycle through TODO states
          ‘+’   Defer 1 day          Push to tomorrow (time-based items only)
          ‘s’   Set date             Pick new date (time-based items only)
          ‘I’   Clock in             Start time tracking
          ‘O’   Clock out            Stop time tracking
          ‘e’   Set effort           Estimate duration
          ‘,’   Set priority         Set A/B/C priority
          ‘:’   Set tags             Add/modify tags
          ‘z’   Add note             Append timestamped note
          ‘a’   Area of focus        Set life area
          ‘c’   Clarify (refile)     Re-clarify and refile
          ‘C’   Clarify (in place)   Re-clarify, keep location
          ‘q’   Quit                 Close the menu

        • Suggested Keybinding

          The command isn't bound by default because org-agenda-mode
          already has many keybindings.  The suggested binding is ‘C-c
          .’ which follows the ‘C-c’ prefix convention for user
          bindings:

               (define-key org-agenda-mode-map (kbd "C-c .") #'org-gtd-agenda-transient)


