5.4.8 Graph View Command Reference
----------------------------------

This is the complete command reference for expert users.

   *Most operations require the transient menu:* Press ‘?’ to access all
commands.

   • Opening Graph View

     ‘M-x org-gtd-show-project-graph’

     *Requires*: Point must be on a project heading (not a task), or
     will prompt for project selection

     *Creates*: Interactive SVG buffer named ‘*Org GTD Graph:
     <project-name>*’

   • Tier 1: Single-Key Commands (Always Available)

     These are the most frequently used commands, available without any
     prefix.

     *Navigation:*

     Key     Command            Description
     ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
     n       Down dependency    Move to a task this one blocks
     p       Up dependency      Move to a task that blocks this one
     TAB     Next sibling       Next sibling task (see ‘org-gtd-graph-sibling-mode’)
     S-TAB   Previous sibling   Previous sibling task
     G       Goto node          Jump to task by name (with completion)

     *What counts as a "sibling"?*  By default, siblings are tasks that
     share at least one blocker (tasks blocked by the same thing).  You
     can customize this with ‘org-gtd-graph-sibling-mode’.  See *note
     Sibling Mode Configuration: org-gtd-graph-sibling-mode.

     *Add Tasks:*

     Key   Command         Description
     -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
     r     Add root task   Create task with no dependencies (starts immediately)
     s     Add successor   Create task that the selected task must complete first
     b     Add blocker     Create task that must complete before selected task

     *Understanding successors and blockers:*

     These two commands handle all dependency relationships:

        • *Add successor* (‘s’): "What comes after this task?"  Creates
          a new task that depends on the selected task.  The selected
          task blocks the new task.

        • *Add blocker* (‘b’): "What must happen first?"  Creates a new
          task that the selected task depends on.  The new task blocks
          the selected task.

     Both commands:
       1. Prompt you to select an existing task OR type a new task title
       2. If creating new: ask whether to clarify/organize it or create
          as simple action
       3. Let you choose multiple edges (which tasks to connect) via
          checkbox menu
       4. Automatically refresh the graph

     *After adding*: Graph automatically refreshes to show new task and
     dependencies.

     *Modify Relationships:*

     Key   Command             Description
     ------------------------------------------------------------------------
     B     Modify blockers     Toggle which tasks block the selected task
     S     Modify successors   Toggle which tasks the selected task blocks

     These commands open a checkbox menu showing all project tasks.
     Toggle checkboxes to add/remove relationships, then press ‘RET’ to
     apply.

     *View:*

     Key   Command            Description
     ----------------------------------------------------------------------
     ?     Show menu          Display transient menu with all commands
     g     Refresh            Rebuild graph (use after external changes)
     v     Toggle rendering   Switch between SVG and ASCII rendering
     q     Quit               Close graph view, keep buffer

   • Tier 2: Prefixed Commands

     These commands are used less frequently and use key prefixes for
     organization.

     *Task Operations (‘t’ prefix):*

     Key   Command               Description
     ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
     t t   Change TODO state     Cycle through TODO states
     t r   Remove from project   Remove task from this project (keeps task)
     t d   Trash task            Mark task canceled and remove from all projects
     t e   Edit in org file      Jump to task in org file for editing
     t i   Show relationships    Display all relationships for selected task

     *Project Operation:*

     Key   Command            Description
     ------------------------------------------------------------------
     I     Incubate project   Move entire project to tickler/someday

     *Graph View Operations:*

     Key   Command         Description
     ----------------------------------------------------------
     Q     Quit and kill   Close graph view and kill buffer
     x s   Export SVG      Export graph as SVG file
     x d   Export DOT      Export graph as Graphviz DOT file
     x a   Export ASCII    Export graph as ASCII text file

   • Visual Indicators

        • *Blue boxes*: NEXT tasks (ready to work on)
        • *Orange boxes*: TODO tasks (blocked by dependencies)
        • *Arrows*: Dependencies (from blocker → blocked task)
        • *Layers*: Vertical positioning shows dependency depth

   • Operations Not Available in Graph View

     Some operations are standard org-mode functionality and must be
     done in the org file:

     *Changing task properties*:
        • TODO state: Use ‘t t’ in graph view, or ‘C-c C-t’ in org file
        • Deadlines/schedules: ‘C-c C-d’, ‘C-c C-s’ in org file
        • Task title/description: edit in org file
        • Tags/properties: edit in org file

     *Task removal*: Use ‘t r’ to remove a task from the project (keeps
     task) or ‘t d’ to trash it (marks canceled).  Completed tasks still
     show in graph view to maintain project history.

     *Access org file*: Press ‘RET’ on any task in graph view to jump to
     it in the org file.

   • Text-Based Alternatives

     Most users will find the graph view intuitive for dependency
     management.  However, DWIM (Do What I Mean) commands work from any
     context (org buffer, agenda, or graph view):

        • ‘org-gtd-project-add-successor’ - Add a task that depends on
          current task
        • ‘org-gtd-project-add-blocker’ - Add a task that blocks current
          task
        • ‘org-gtd-project-add-root-task’ - Add a task with no
          dependencies
        • ‘org-gtd-project-remove-task’ - Remove task from project
          (keeps task)
        • ‘org-gtd-project-trash-task’ - Remove and cancel task
        • ‘org-gtd-project-change-state’ - Change TODO state

     For lower-level dependency manipulation:

        • ‘org-gtd-task-add-blockers’ - Add blockers via text interface
        • ‘org-gtd-task-remove-blockers’ - Remove blockers via text
          interface
        • ‘org-gtd-task-show-relationships’ - Display relationships in
          minibuffer
        • ‘org-gtd-validate-project-dependencies’ - Validate project
          structure

     See *note Task Dependency Commands:: for details.


