6.1.4 Organize and Process Configuration
----------------------------------------

   • ‘org-gtd-organize-hooks’

     *Type*: List of functions

     *Default*: ‘'(org-set-tags-command)’

     *Description*: Functions run when organizing each item.  Each
     function can add metadata (tags, properties, etc.)  to the item
     being organized.

     The default value prompts for tags.  Built-in options:
     ‘org-set-tags-command’
          Prompt for tags (default)
     ‘org-gtd-set-area-of-focus’
          Prompt for area of focus
     Custom functions
          Functions you write yourself

     *Example*: Add effort estimation and area of focus:
          (defun my-add-effort ()
            "Prompt for effort when organizing."
            (when (org-gtd-organize-type-member-p '(single-action project-heading))
              (org-set-effort)))

          (setq org-gtd-organize-hooks
                '(org-set-tags-command
                  org-gtd-set-area-of-focus
                  my-add-effort))

     *Helper function*: ‘org-gtd-organize-type-member-p’
        • Takes a list of item types to check against
        • Returns t if current item matches one of the types
        • Available types: ‘single-action’, ‘project-heading’,
          ‘project-task’, ‘calendar’, ‘delegated’, ‘tickler’, ‘someday’,
          ‘habit’, ‘knowledge’, ‘quick-action’, ‘trash’, ‘everything’

   • ‘org-gtd-save-after-organize’

     *Type*: Boolean

     *Default*: ‘nil’

     *Description*: If non-nil, save all modified buffers after each
     organize step.

     Useful if you want automatic saves during inbox processing.

     *Example*:
          (setq org-gtd-save-after-organize t)

   • ‘org-gtd-refile-to-any-target’ (deprecated)

     *Type*: Boolean

     *Default*: ‘t’

     *Deprecated*: As of 4.0.0.  Use ‘org-gtd-refile-prompt-for-types’
     instead.

     *Description*: Control refile behavior when organizing items.  This
     variable is deprecated and will show a warning when used.

        • When ‘t’: org-gtd will refile to the first target it finds
          without prompting (deprecated behavior)
        • When ‘nil’: org-gtd consults ‘org-gtd-refile-prompt-for-types’
          to decide per item type

     *Migration*: To migrate to the new system:

          ;; Step 1: Set the deprecated variable to nil (required)
          ;; This enables per-type control via org-gtd-refile-prompt-for-types
          (setq org-gtd-refile-to-any-target nil)

          ;; Step 2 (optional): Customize which types prompt
          ;; The default prompts for most types except quick-action, knowledge, trash
          ;; Only change this if you want different behavior:
          ;; (setq org-gtd-refile-prompt-for-types '(project-heading project-task))

     See *note Controlling Refile Prompts by Item Type:: for the new
     approach.

   • ‘org-gtd-refile-prompt-for-types’

     *Type*: List of symbols

     *Default*: ‘(single-action project-heading project-task calendar
     someday delegated tickler habit)’

     *Description*: List of GTD item types that should prompt for refile
     target selection when organizing.

        • Types in the list prompt user to choose from available refile
          targets
        • Types *not* in the list auto-refile to the first available
          target
        • Only consulted when ‘org-gtd-refile-to-any-target’ is ‘nil’

     *Valid type symbols:* ‘single-action’, ‘project-heading’,
     ‘project-task’, ‘calendar’, ‘someday’, ‘delegated’, ‘tickler’,
     ‘habit’, ‘knowledge’, ‘quick-action’, ‘trash’

     *Example*: Only prompt for projects, auto-refile everything else:

          (setq org-gtd-refile-prompt-for-types '(project-heading project-task))

     *Example*: Add knowledge items to prompt list (they auto-refile by
     default):

          (setq org-gtd-refile-prompt-for-types
                '(single-action project-heading project-task calendar
                  someday delegated tickler habit knowledge))

     See *note Controlling Refile Prompts by Item Type:: for detailed
     examples.


