6.1.13 Graph View Configuration
-------------------------------

These variables control the project graph visualization feature.

   • ‘org-gtd-graph-render-mode’

     *Type*: Symbol

     *Default*: ‘'svg’

     *Description*: Default rendering mode for project dependency
     graphs.

     Values:
     ‘'svg’
          High-quality graphical rendering (requires GUI Emacs)
     ‘'ascii’
          Text-based rendering using box-drawing characters (works in
          terminal)

     You can toggle between modes in any graph buffer by pressing ‘v’.

     *Example*:
          ;; Use ASCII mode by default (good for terminal users)
          (setq org-gtd-graph-render-mode 'ascii)

     *See also*: *note Graph Rendering Modes:: for detailed comparison.

   • ‘org-gtd-graph-ui-split-ratio’

     *Type*: Float (0.0 to 1.0)

     *Default*: ‘0.7’

     *Description*: Width ratio for the graph window when showing
     project graphs.

     The graph view displays two panels: the dependency graph and a
     details panel showing the selected task.  This ratio controls how
     much horizontal space the graph takes.

        • ‘0.7’ means the graph takes 70% of width, details take 30%
          (default)
        • ‘0.5’ would give equal space to both
        • ‘0.8’ would give more space to the graph

     *Example*:
          ;; Give more space to the details panel
          (setq org-gtd-graph-ui-split-ratio 0.6)

   • ‘org-gtd-graph-sibling-mode’

     *Type*: Symbol

     *Default*: ‘'any-same-blocker’

     *Description*: How to determine sibling tasks for TAB/S-TAB
     navigation in graph view.

     When you press TAB or S-TAB in graph view, you move between
     "sibling" tasks.  This variable controls what counts as a sibling:

     Values:
     ‘'any-same-blocker’
          Tasks sharing at least one blocker (default).  Two tasks are
          siblings if they have any blocker in common.  This groups
          tasks that are conceptually related through shared
          prerequisites.
     ‘'all-same-blockers’
          Tasks with exactly the same set of blockers.  Two tasks are
          siblings only if their blocker sets are identical.  This is
          stricter and shows only tasks that are truly parallel
          alternatives.
     ‘'dag-level’
          Tasks at the same depth in the dependency graph.  Two tasks
          are siblings if they have the same layer number, regardless of
          their actual blockers.  This gives a visual/structural
          grouping.

     *Example*:
          ;; Default: share any blocker
          (setq org-gtd-graph-sibling-mode 'any-same-blocker)

          ;; Strict: exact same blockers only
          (setq org-gtd-graph-sibling-mode 'all-same-blockers)

          ;; Structural: same depth in graph
          (setq org-gtd-graph-sibling-mode 'dag-level)

     *When to use each mode*:

        • *any-same-blocker (default)*: Best for most users.  When
          you're on "Write tests" and press TAB, you'll see other tasks
          that also depend on "Set up project"—tasks you could work on
          in parallel after finishing the blocker.

        • *all-same-blockers*: Use when you want strict parallelism.
          Only shows tasks that are truly equivalent alternatives—same
          prerequisites, same position in the workflow.

        • *dag-level*: Use when you think visually about your project.
          Groups all tasks at the same "layer" or depth, regardless of
          their actual dependencies.

     *See also*: *note Graph View Command Reference:: for navigation
     keybindings.


