6.2.13 Project Management Commands
----------------------------------

   • ‘org-gtd-projects-fix-todo-keywords-for-project-at-point’

     *When to use*: When project TODO states seem incorrect after
     dependency changes

     *What it does*:
        • Recalculates which tasks should be NEXT based on dependency
          graph
        • Updates all task keywords in the project
        • Fixes stuck projects

     *Required*: Point must be on project heading

     *Note*: This is automatically called after graph UI operations and
     text-based task management commands.  You typically only need this
     for troubleshooting edge cases.

   • ‘org-gtd-projects-fix-all-todo-keywords’

     **What it is:** Recalculates and fixes TODO/NEXT states for ALL
     projects in your GTD system at once.

     **Why you'd use it:** After making changes in external tools
     (mobile apps, web interfaces, other editors) that don't know about
     org-gtd's dependency logic, your task states might be inconsistent.
     This command makes everything sane again.

     **Who needs it:** Anyone who edits their GTD files outside of
     org-gtd (mobile apps, sync conflicts, manual edits).

     **Your first use (30 seconds):**

       1. Edit tasks on your phone/tablet/other tool
       2. Sync back to Emacs
       3. Run: ‘M-x org-gtd-projects-fix-all-todo-keywords’
       4. Done - all task states are now correct

     That's it.  No need to manually check each project.

     **Common scenarios:**

        • Completed tasks on mobile → states might be wrong → run this
        • Changed task descriptions/notes externally → run this to be
          safe
        • Sync conflict resolution → run this after fixing conflicts
        • Bulk manual edits outside org-gtd → run this
        • After migration or data import → run this

     **When to use this vs the single-project version:**

     Use ‘org-gtd-projects-fix-all-todo-keywords’ when:
        • You've worked in external tools (mobile, web, other editors)
        • You've edited multiple projects
        • You don't know which projects are affected
        • You want to fix everything at once (safest option)

     Use ‘org-gtd-projects-fix-todo-keywords-for-project-at-point’ when:
        • You know which specific project has issues
        • You've just edited one project in Emacs
        • You want to fix just one project quickly

     **What it does (technical):**

       1. Scans all projects in agenda files
       2. Resets active task states (TODO/NEXT → TODO)
       3. Calculates which tasks are ready based on dependencies
       4. Marks ready tasks as NEXT
       5. Preserves user-set states (WAIT, DONE, CNCL)
       6. Handles multi-project tasks correctly (AND semantics)

     **Multi-project tasks:**

     Some tasks can belong to multiple projects.  This command handles
     them safely:
        • Shared task becomes NEXT only if ready in ALL its projects
        • If ready in just some projects, stays TODO
        • WAIT states are never auto-changed

     **When NOT to use:**

        • If you only work in Emacs with org-gtd commands (automatic
          state management works)
        • If your projects look correct already
        • Before making external changes (use after, not before)

   • ‘org-gtd-project-update-all-cookies’

     **What it is:** Refreshes progress cookies on ALL project headings
     at once.

     **Why you'd use it:** Progress cookies show ‘[3/7][42%]’ on project
     headings.  While these update automatically when you change task
     states, sometimes you want to refresh everything—for example, after
     bulk changes or data migration.

     **Your first use (30 seconds):**

       1. Run: ‘M-x org-gtd-project-update-all-cookies’
       2. Done - all project headings now show accurate progress

     **What it does:**

        • Scans all projects in agenda files
        • Counts completed vs total tasks for each project
        • Updates the ‘[completed/total][percent%]’ display on each
          project heading

     **When to use:**

        • After bulk task changes outside of org-gtd
        • After data migration or import
        • During weekly review for visual refresh
        • If progress cookies look outdated

     **Configuration:**

     Progress cookies are controlled by
     ‘org-gtd-project-progress-cookie-position’:
        • ‘'end’ (default) - cookies appear at end of heading before
          tags
        • ‘'start’ - cookies appear after TODO keyword
        • ‘nil’ - cookies disabled entirely

     *See also*: *note Project Progress Cookies: Project Progress
     Cookies See Your Progress at a Glance. for detailed usage guide.

   • ‘org-gtd-tickler’

     **What it is:** Smart command to pause items with a specific review
     date (time-based reminder).

     **Why you'd use it:** You have a project or action that's a good
     idea, but not ready NOW.  You want to set it aside with a specific
     date to review it later, without losing your planning work.

     **Who needs it:** Anyone managing items that need to be deferred
     until a specific time or date.

     **Your first use (30 seconds):**

       1. Navigate to a project or action
       2. Run: ‘M-x org-gtd-tickler’
       3. Enter review date: ‘2025-12-01’
       4. Done - it disappears from your engage view until that date

     **What it does:**

     Detects what you're on:
        • Project heading → ticklers entire project with all tasks
        • Project task → ticklers the project it belongs to
        • Single action → ticklers just that action

     For projects:
        • Preserves all task states and dependencies
        • Hides everything from engage/NEXT views
        • Adds review date to your agenda
        • Skips multi-project tasks (tasks shared between projects)

     **When to use:**

        • Projects you want to start on a specific future date
        • Seasonal projects (start each year at a certain time)
        • Projects blocked by external factors with an expected
          resolution date
        • Items you want to reconsider after a specific event or
          milestone

     **Note:** For items with NO specific timeframe ("maybe someday"),
     use ‘org-gtd-someday’ instead.

   • ‘org-gtd-reactivate’

     **What it is:** Bring back tickler or someday items to their
     original active state.

     **Why you'd use it:** You're ready to work on something you
     previously set aside—either a tickler item whose review date
     arrived, or a someday item you've decided to act on.

     **Your first use (30 seconds):**

       1. Navigate to a tickler or someday item
       2. Run: ‘M-x org-gtd-reactivate’
       3. For non-project items: confirm or update each saved property
          when prompted
       4. For projects: graph view opens for review

     **What it does:**

     *For all items:*
        • Restores original ‘ORG_GTD’ value from ‘PREVIOUS_ORG_GTD’
        • Restores TODO keyword from ‘PREVIOUS_TODO’
        • Removes ‘ORG_GTD_TIMESTAMP’ (tickler review date)

     *For non-project items (delegated, calendar, single actions):*
        • Prompts you to confirm or update each type-specific property
        • Example: "Delegated to [Jane Smith]: " lets you keep Jane or
          enter someone new
        • Example: "Scheduled _[2025-03-15 Sat]_: " lets you update the
          date

     *For projects:*
        • Iterates over all project tasks restoring each one
        • Recalculates NEXT tasks based on current dependencies
        • Opens project graph view for review

     **When to use:**

        • When a tickler item appears in your agenda on its review date
        • During someday/maybe review when you decide to activate an
          item
        • When you're ready to reactivate something earlier than
          scheduled
        • During weekly review when scanning tickler or someday items

     **Note:** If an item has no saved state (‘PREVIOUS_ORG_GTD’ is
     empty), reactivation will start the organize workflow so you can
     categorize it fresh.


