6.5.4 Filter Reference
----------------------

The following sections document all available filters.  Use them to
build the exact view you need.

   • View Structure

     A GTD view is defined as an alist with filters at the top level:

          ;; Simple view with filters at top level
          '((name . "View Name")
            (type . delegated)
            (when . past))

     Multiple filters create AND logic (all must match).

        • Multi-Block Views

          For complex views with multiple sections (like the engage
          view), use ‘blocks’:

               '((name . "My Custom Dashboard")
                 (blocks . (((name . "Today's Calendar")
                             (block-type . calendar-day))
                            ((name . "Items Due Today")
                             (type . delegated)
                             (when . today))
                            ((name . "All NEXT Actions")
                             (type . next-action)))))

          Each block is its own view spec.  Blocks are displayed in
          order as separate agenda sections.

        • Block Types

          Special ‘block-type’ values control how blocks are rendered:

          ‘calendar-day’
               Native org-agenda day view filtered to Calendar and Habit
               items only
          ‘todo’
               Native org-agenda todo block (requires ‘todo-keyword’)
          _default_
               tags block with skip function (when no block-type
               specified)

        • Native Blocks (Escape Hatch)

          Have you ever wanted your NEXT actions sorted by priority?  Or
          needed a custom skip function for a specialized workflow?  The
          DSL handles most cases, but org-agenda has decades of
          features.  When you hit its limits, ‘native’ blocks let you
          drop down to raw org-agenda syntax--without abandoning the DSL
          entirely.

             • When You'll Need This

               You're building a view and think: "I wish I could sort
               these by effort" or "I need my custom skip function
               here."  The DSL doesn't support sorting yet.  What do you
               do?

               You have two choices:
                 1. Write the whole view in ‘org-agenda-custom-commands’
                    (losing DSL benefits)
                 2. Use a ‘native’ block for just that section (keeping
                    DSL for the rest)

               Option 2 is what this section teaches.

             • Your First Native Block

               Start with something you know.  This DSL block shows NEXT
               actions:

                    ((type . next-action))

               Here's the equivalent as a native block:

                    ((native . (tags-todo "LEVEL>0+ORG_GTD=\"Actions\"/NEXT" nil)))

               The format is ‘(BLOCK-TYPE MATCH-STRING
               SETTINGS)’--exactly what ‘org-agenda-custom-commands’
               uses.  Try evaluating both in a multi-block view:

                    (org-gtd-view-show
                     '((name . "Comparing DSL and Native")
                       (blocks . (((name . "DSL Version")
                                   (type . next-action))
                                  ((native . (tags-todo "LEVEL>0+ORG_GTD=\"Actions\"/NEXT"
                                              ((org-agenda-overriding-header "Native Version")))))))))

               They show the same items.  The native block is more
               verbose, but it unlocks org-agenda's full power.

             • Adding Custom Sorting

               Now the payoff.  Want priority sorting?  Add it to the
               settings list:

                    ((native . (tags-todo "+@work/NEXT"
                                ((org-agenda-sorting-strategy '(priority-down effort-up))
                                 (org-agenda-overriding-header "Work by Priority")))))

               The settings list can include any org-agenda variable.
               Common ones:
                  • ‘org-agenda-sorting-strategy’ -- Sort by priority,
                    effort, alphabetically
                  • ‘org-agenda-skip-function’ -- Your custom skip logic
                  • ‘org-agenda-prefix-format’ -- Custom prefix display

             • Mixing DSL and Native

               The real power is mixing them.  Use DSL for simple
               blocks, native for complex ones:

                    (org-gtd-view-show
                     '((name . "Mixed Dashboard")
                       (blocks . (((type . delegated)                               ; DSL: simple
                                   (when . past))
                                  ((native . (tags-todo "+urgent"                   ; Native: sorted
                                              ((org-agenda-sorting-strategy '(effort-up))
                                               (org-agenda-overriding-header "Urgent by Effort")))))
                                  ((type . next-action))))))                        ; DSL: simple

               Each block is independent.  Use whatever syntax fits that
               block's needs.

             • Native Block Types

               The BLOCK-TYPE (first element) determines what kind of
               agenda block you get:

               Block Type    What It Shows
               -------------------------------------------------------
               ‘agenda’      Calendar/timeline (like daily view)
               ‘todo’        TODO items by keyword
               ‘tags’        Items matching tag/property expression
               ‘tags-todo’   Like ‘tags’ but only TODO items
               ‘search’      Full-text search results

             • Quick Reference

               *Syntax*:
                    ((native . (BLOCK-TYPE MATCH-STRING SETTINGS)))

               *Rules*:
                  • Only valid inside a ‘blocks’ list
                  • Other DSL keys in the same block spec are ignored
                  • Settings is an alist of ‘(org-agenda-variable
                    value)’ pairs

               *When to use*: Custom sorting, skip functions,
               specialized org-agenda settings, or migrating complex
               views incrementally


