6.5.14 View Configuration Options
---------------------------------

These options control how the view is displayed:

   • ‘(block-type . TYPE)’

     *Purpose*: Control how a block is rendered

     *Values*:
     ‘calendar-day’
          Native org-agenda day view filtered to Calendar and Habit
          items
     ‘todo’
          Native org-agenda todo block (requires ‘todo-keyword’)
     _omit_
          Default tags block with skip function

     *Use case*: When you need native agenda features (time grid,
     habits, etc.)

     *Example*: Multi-block view with calendar:
          '((name . "My Dashboard")
            (blocks . (((name . "Today's Schedule")
                        (block-type . calendar-day))
                       ((name . "Delegated Due Today")
                        (type . delegated)
                        (when . today)))))

   • ‘(blocks . BLOCK-LIST)’

     *Purpose*: Create a multi-section view with multiple blocks

     *Format*: List of view specs, each with its own name and filters

     *Example*:
          '((name . "Review Dashboard")
            (blocks . (((name . "Stuck Projects")
                        (type . stuck-project))
                       ((name . "Missed Delegated")
                        (type . delegated)
                        (when . past))
                       ((name . "Upcoming Calendar")
                        (type . calendar)
                        (when . future)))))

   • Prefix DSL: Customizing the Task Prefix Column

     When you look at your engage view, you see context information on
     the left of each task--like the project name.  The Prefix DSL lets
     you control what appears there using a simple fallback chain.

     *Mental model:* Think of the prefix like a label maker.  You
     specify what you _want_ to show, in order of preference.  org-gtd
     tries each option until one has a value.

        • Your First Prefix in 60 Seconds

          Try this now (evaluate with ‘M-x eval-region’):

               (org-gtd-view-show
                '((name . "Tasks with Context")
                  (prefix . (project area-of-focus "—"))
                  (type . next-action)))

          You'll see NEXT actions with:
             • The project name (if the task is in a project)
             • Or the area of focus (if no project, but area is set)
             • Or a dash "—" (if neither is available)

          That's the fallback chain in action.

        • ‘(prefix . (ELEMENT ...))’

          *Purpose*: Control what context appears before each task in
          the view

          *Format*: A list of elements, tried in order.  First non-empty
          value wins.

          *Available elements*:
          ‘project’
               The project heading this task belongs to
          ‘area-of-focus’
               The ‘CATEGORY’ property (your GTD area of focus)
          ‘file-name’
               The base name of the file containing the task
          ‘"literal string"’
               Any quoted string (used as fallback)

          *Example*: Show project, fallback to area, then to literal
          text:
               '((name . "My View")
                 (prefix . (project area-of-focus "No Context"))
                 (type . next-action))

          *Example*: Just show the project name (or nothing):
               '((name . "Project Tasks")
                 (prefix . (project))
                 (type . next-action))

          *Example*: Tickler items labeled "Incubated":
               '((name . "Tickler Items")
                 (prefix . ("Incubated"))
                 (type . tickler))

        • ‘(prefix-width . N)’

          *Purpose*: Control how many characters the prefix column uses

          *Default*: Uses ‘org-gtd-prefix-width’ (default: 12)

          *Note*: Long values are truncated with "…".  Short values are
          padded with spaces.

          *Example*: Extra space for long project names:
               '((name . "Wide Prefix View")
                 (prefix . (project area-of-focus))
                 (prefix-width . 20)
                 (type . next-action))

        • Prefix Inheritance in Multi-Block Views

          When you define ‘prefix’ at the view level, all blocks inherit
          it:

               '((name . "My Dashboard")
                 (prefix . (project area-of-focus "—"))  ;; All blocks use this
                 (prefix-width . 15)
                 (blocks . (((name . "Calendar Today")
                             (type . calendar)
                             (when . today))
                            ((name . "NEXT Actions")
                             (type . next-action)))))

          Individual blocks can override the inherited prefix:

               '((name . "Mixed Prefixes")
                 (prefix . (project))  ;; Default for blocks
                 (blocks . (((name . "Projects")
                             (prefix . ("Project"))  ;; Override: literal label
                             (type . active-project))
                            ((name . "NEXT Actions")
                             ;; Uses inherited (project) prefix
                             (type . next-action)))))

        • Low-Level: ‘(prefix-format . FORMAT-STRING)’

          For advanced users who need full control, you can specify the
          raw org-agenda prefix format string.  This bypasses the prefix
          DSL.

          *Example*:
               '((name . "Custom Format")
                 (prefix-format . " %i %-12:(org-gtd-agenda--prefix-format 12) ")
                 (blocks . (((name . "NEXT Actions")
                             (type . next-action)))))

          Most users should use ‘(prefix . ...)’ instead.

   • ‘(view-type . agenda)’

     *Purpose*: Create a day/week org-agenda view instead of a tags
     block

     *Use case*: When you want a standard day/week agenda view

     *Example*:
          '((name . "Weekly Agenda")
            (view-type . agenda)
            (agenda-span . 7))

   • ‘(agenda-span . N)’

     *Purpose*: Number of days to show in agenda view

     *Default*: 1

     *Requires*: ‘(view-type . agenda)’


